  "prompt": "Does being good at mathematics make you intelligent?",
  "response": "Being good at mathematics can be an indicator of certain types of intelligence, particularly logical reasoning and problem-solving skills. It demonstrates an ability to recognize patterns, abstract concepts, and manipulate equations\u2014skills that are valued in many areas of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM).\n\nHowever, intelligence is a multifaceted concept that encompasses various abilities and types of reasoning. For example, emotional intelligence, linguistic intelligence, spatial intelligence, and social intelligence are all important in different contexts and can be exhibited by individuals who may not excel in mathematics.\n\nIn summary, while proficiency in mathematics can indicate certain cognitive strengths, it is not the sole measure of intelligence, and individuals can demonstrate intelligence in many other ways.",
